3.30pm Play has been called off. Bad news folks, that's it for today.

Eusha: "There's no doubt Khwaja is unlucky! He's stuck on 13!" Shaun Marsh finished the day 13 short of a hundred yesterday.

Thanks all for tuning in and sending us the esoteric info about weather, archery and what not. Should be an early start tomorrow, we'll be back at 9.30am. See you then.

And last mail before logging out. Sid Boyce: "Cyprus for no rain, against that the pitches and the grounds. Other than for the cricket it's a great feeling to know that between the end of April and the end of September you don't have to think of an umbrella or raincoat. The rest of the year the rain gods turn the taps on. Still I love the place."

3.15pm Chances of play today getting bleaker.

Chandana: "Forget the cricket for a moment folks. England are trailing Argentina 3:9 in NZ. Yes the Rugby Union World Cup 2011 is in full swing :) cheers." And you can follow that on our sister site Scrum.

Geoff Marsh on watching Shaun making a hundred: "That's got to be the highlight of my life." Dan Brettig has that and more in his latest tour diary.

2.55pm Tom Moody says "Rain is getting more consistent here in Kandy looks very unlikely we will see the players out again today."

Around the world with Cricinfo continues. Here's Umesh from Cyprus: "It hasn't rained here in 6 months. why these teams don't come to visit Cyprus and play rest of the match. Cypriots are keen to play cricket due to the dry weather these days."

Getting further and further away from cricket.Robert Brown: "Have Raced horses in Darwin, the wet season really takes hold from November and yes they still race in the wet season, the track is oil based and the water runs off, and they still run quick times, very humid and the wet season in Darwin is called the silly season, drives people mad and sometimes people do very silly things, it has a high rate of suicide during the period. True."

2.45pm Geoff Marsh isn't in town just to watch his son bat. He is in talks to be Sri Lanka's coach. Read all about it here.

In praise of archers. Shax: "It's raining here in Thimphu, Bhutan at the moment, too. Hasn't stopped the archery matches, though. Hardier than cricketers, these Bhutanese!" And hardier than tennis players too.

When was the last time Darwin got this much attention from Cricinfo readers. Andrew Symonds' fishing trip? Brett Steinhert: "I have lived in Darwin for 10 years. Darwin's climate is tropical savannah because of the length of the dry season from may to september where on average 50mm occurs in this period. A tropical rainforest climate occurs where rainfall is greater than 60mm in every month (Kandy). Darwin receives 1800mm from Oct-Apr on average, so it is a tropical wet and dry climate."

2.35pm Update (of sorts): Still the same in Pallekele, full ground covers on as it continues to rain. Dan Brettig says: "Can't see much play on horizon." Tea has been taken

If they could packup right now and move to Vienna, the next 3 days are for sunny and warm with upto 30 degrees."

And for those of you asking about the weather over the next two days. It's not good news. BBC had predicted "light rain shower" today, it's "heavy rain shower" tomorrow and, hold your breath, "thunder storm" on Monday.

Laks gives us a lesson on Sri Lanka weather: "@gazza it's not that simple. There are 2 rainy season in Sri Lanka, and one which affects the south west, and one which affects the north east. To further complicate matters, some areas (zones) can be drier than others in the same region. However, as Sri Lanka experiences a tropical climate, as opposed to the sub-tropical of Darwin, torrential rain may strike in any season or zone. "
